First, I installed all the required libraries and packages needed to learn and understand RAG, LangChain, LangGraph, and related technologies.
I installed the UV package manager to create and manage a virtual environment for the project.

Virtual Environment
A virtual environment is an isolated Python workspace that has its own Python interpreter and installed packages. 
It allows each project to use different package versions without affecting other projects or the system-wide Python installation.

UV Package manager : if is defined as fast python and project manager written in rust.
A single tool to replace pip, pip-tools, pipx, poetry, pyenv, twine, virtualenv, and more.
Common commands used by uv are : 
. uv venv (to create virtual Environment)
. .venv\Scripts\activate (this is used to activate)
. uv add langchain (used to install a package)

Difference betweeen UV and PIP:

                      UV                                                    PIP
Package, environment, and project manager                             Package installer
    Much faster (written in Rust)                                        Slower
       Built in (uv venv)                                            uses venv separately
      Installed separately                                          Usually comes with python
